Adaptation considered: Climate features: Economic dynamics: Impact interactions: Space disaggregation: Impact persistence: Hazard definition: More Notes: Highlights: Methodology: Approach: Category: Drivers of Risk: Outcome(s) of Interest: Life cycle assessment (LCA) results indicated that the Fe-CatOx-BC-RF pilot system is a BC dose-dependent carbon-negative technology at −1.21 kg CO2e/m3... demonstrating potential as a biochar dose-dependent negative emissions technology... the potential of carbon negativity to become a water treatment performance standard as important and attainable as pollutant and pathogen removal. Practitioner Points: Life cycle assessment (LCA) of a pilot scale tertiary biochar water treatment process with or without catalytic ozonation at a WRRF shows a carbon negative global warming potential of −1.21-kg CO2e/m3 while removing 90%–99% TP and >90% of detected micropollutants. Biochar-integrated reactive filtration use can aid in long-term carbon sequestration by reducing the carbon footprint of advanced water treatment in a dose-dependent manner, allowing an overall carbon-neutral or carbon-negative process.; "LCA results indicated that the Fe-CatOx-BC-RF pilot system is a BC dose-dependent carbon-negative technology..."; "For the WRRF-installed RF system, modeled with the same rate of BC addition, the overall process changed..."; "Using the C100 100-year carbon accounting approach rather than Cnet reduces these CO2e metrics..."; "Using the same BC dose in an estimation of a 3780 m3/day (1 MGD) ... the carbon neutral cost of treatment is reduced further..."; LCA results indicated that the Fe-CatOx-BC-RF pilot system is a BC dose-dependent carbon-negative technology at −1.21 kg CO2e/m3...For the WRRF-installed RF system, modeled with the same rate of BC addition, the overall process changed from 0.02 kg CO2e/m3 to a carbon negative −1.41 kg CO2e/m3...; Life cycle assessment (LCA) and techno-economic analysis (TEA) models are developed for a tertiary wastewater treatment system... In this work, we conduct an ISO-compliant LCA... A stochastic TEA for the cost of water treatment using this combinatorial P removal/recovery, micropollutant destructive removal, and disinfection advanced technology shows that at scale, the mean cost...; Life cycle assessment (LCA) and techno-economic analysis (TEA) models are developed for a tertiary wastewater treatment system that employs a biochar-integrated reactive filtration (RF) approach... In this work, we conduct an ISO-compliant LCA of a 49.2 m3/day (9 gpm) field pilot-scale Fe-CatOx-BC-RF system and a 1130 m3/day (0.3 MGD) water resource recovery facility (WRRF)-installed RF system, modeled with BC addition at the same rate of 0.45 g/L to quantify their environmental impacts... Techno-economic analysis (TEA) of this biochar catalytic oxidation reactive filtration process using Monte Carlo stochastic modeling shows a forecasted carbon-neutral process cost...; LCA of a pilot scale tertiary biochar water treatment process with or without catalytic ozonation at a WRRF shows a carbon negative global warming potential of −1.21-kg CO2e/m3 while removing 90%–99% TP and >90% of detected micropollutants; Biochar-integrated reactive filtration use can aid in long-term carbon sequestration by reducing the carbon footprint of advanced water treatment in a dose-dependent manner, allowing an overall carbon-neutral or carbon-negative process; TEA of this biochar catalytic oxidation reactive filtration process using Monte Carlo stochastic modeling shows a forecasted carbon-neutral process cost with low P and micropollutant removal as US$0.11/m3 ± 0.01 for a 3780-m3/day (1 MGD) scale installation with BC cost at US$0.03/m3 of that total; The results demonstrate the potential of carbon negativity to become a water treatmentperformance standard as important and attainable as pollutant and pathogen removal.; Life cycle assessment (LCA) results indicated that the Fe-CatOx-BC-RF pilot system is a BC dose-dependent carbon-negative technology at −1.21 kg CO2e/m3, where biochar addition constitutes a −1.53 kg/m3 CO2e beneficial impact to the process. [...] the results demonstrate the potential of carbon negativity to become a water treatment performance standard as important and attainable as pollutant and pathogen removal.; There is no mention of specific climate hazards (acute shocks, chronic trends, or stylized changes) that are being analyzed or addressed by the system.; "Biochar-integrated reactive filtration use can aid in long-term carbon sequestration by reducing the carbon footprint of advanced water treatment in a dose-dependent manner, allowing an overall carbon-neutral or carbon-negative process."; There is no source material that supports regional or global analysis. The analysis is focused on a 49.2 m3/day field pilot-scale system and a 1130 m3/day WRRF-installed system.; 
Life cycle assessment (LCA) and techno-economic analysis (TEA) models are developed for a tertiary wastewater treatment system that employs a biochar-integrated reactive filtration (RF) approach... LCA results indicated that the Fe-CatOx-BC-RF pilot system is a BC dose-dependent carbon-negative technology at −1.21 kg CO2e/m3... For the WRRF-installed RF system, modeled with the same rate of BC addition, the overall process changed from 0.02 kg CO2e/m3 to a carbon negative −1.41 kg CO2e/m3, demonstrating potential as a biochar dose-dependent negative emissions technology. A stochastic TEA for the cost of water treatment using this combinatorial P removal/recovery, micropollutant destructive removal, and disinfection advanced technology shows that at scale, the mean cost for treating 1130 m3/day (0.3 MGD) WRRF secondary influent water with Fe-CatOx-BC-RF using the C100 metric is US$0.18 ± US$0.01/m3 to achieve overall process carbon neutrality.
; The technology demonstrates 90%–99% total phosphorus removals, adsorption of phosphorus to biochar for recovery, and >90% destructive removal of observed micropollutants. In this work, we conduct an ISO-compliant LCA of a 49.2 m3/day (9 gpm) field pilot-scale Fe-CatOx-BC-RF system and a 1130 m3/day (0.3 MGD) water resource recovery facility (WRRF)-installed RF system, modeled with BC addition at the same rate of 0.45 g/L to quantify their environmental impacts. ... A stochastic TEA for the cost of water treatment using this combinatorial P removal/recovery, micropollutant destructive removal, and disinfection advanced technology shows that at scale, the mean cost for treating 1130 m3/day (0.3 MGD) WRRF secondary influent water with Fe-CatOx-BC-RF using the C100 metric is US$0.18 ± US$0.01/m3 to achieve overall process carbon neutrality.; No direct mention of "tipping points" or other complex climate dynamics beyond carbon accounting in the abstract.; "LCA results indicated that the Fe-CatOx-BC-RF pilot system is a BC dose-dependent carbon-negative technology at −1.21 kg CO2e/m3...the overall process changed from 0.02 kg CO2e/m3 to a carbon negative −1.41 kg CO2e/m3, demonstrating potential as a biochar dose-dependent negative emissions technology." and "Biochar-integrated reactive filtration use can aid in long-term carbon sequestration by reducing the carbon footprint of advanced water treatment in a dose-dependent manner, allowing an overall carbon-neutral or carbon-negative process."
